{"term":"1963","caseName":"United States v. Stapf","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1963/54","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - October 23, 1963","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren11/oral_argument_audio/14119","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 54, United States, Petitioner, versus Dorothy Anne Stapf and B. T. Ware, Executors.","start":0,"stop":31.251,"duration":31.25},{"text":"Mr. Barnett.","start":31.251,"stop":33.91,"duration":2.66}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":33.91,"stop":36.402,"duration":2.49},{"text":"This is an estate tax case.","start":36.402,"stop":37.698,"duration":1.3},{"text":"It's here on certiorari to the United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit, involves two entirely separate questions and I will state the facts relevant to each in connection with the discussion of that question.","start":37.698,"stop":49.991,"duration":12.29},{"text":"Both questions are I think very simple one.","start":49.991,"stop":54.992,"duration":5},{"text":"The first question is whether the estate was entitled to a marital deduction and I think that question can be fairly stated as being whether it would be quest of property for surviving wife one condition that she conveys property of equal value to a testator's children qualified for marital deduction.","start":54.992,"stop":80.775,"duration":25.78},{"text":"Lowell H. Stapf, a resident of Texas died in 1953.","start":80.775,"stop":85.449,"duration":4.67},{"text":"He was survived by his wife.","start":85.449,"stop":88.256,"duration":2.81},{"text":"At the date of his death, he owned as in separate property real estate valued at $65,000.","start":88.256,"stop":94.988,"duration":6.73},{"text":"He and his wife together own as community property assets with the total value of $258,000.","start":94.988,"stop":103.481,"duration":8.49},{"text":"His will provided that all of his property, that is his separate property and his half of the community property were to go -- was to go to a trust for the children giving nothing to his wife unless she consented to allow all of the community property to pass according to the terms of the will.","start":103.481,"stop":122.105,"duration":18.62},{"text":"If she did so consent, she was then to receive one third of everything, one third of his separate property, plus one third of the community property.","start":122.105,"stop":131.613,"duration":9.51}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Is she -- is she then to like to take under will what was (Inaudible)?","start":131.613,"stop":133.792,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"She would take only her half of the community property and all of his property, his half of the community property plus his separate property would go to a trust for the children.","start":133.792,"stop":144.727,"duration":10.94}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"I think I understand.","start":144.727,"stop":145.426,"duration":0.7},{"text":"Under the Texas law, what statutory right to say a surviving spouse has?","start":145.426,"stop":150.944,"duration":5.52}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"She is entitled to one-half of all the community property less one-half of the debts.","start":150.944,"stop":156.996,"duration":6.05}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"That --","start":156.996,"stop":157.146,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"Of the community, yes.","start":157.146,"stop":158.697,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And -- and --","start":158.697,"stop":159.099,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"She would have taken -- let me give you the figures.","start":159.099,"stop":162.878,"duration":3.78},{"text":"In this case, had she not taken under the will, had she just stood on her rights, her ownership of community property, she would receive net $111,000 with the property.","start":162.878,"stop":174.296,"duration":11.42}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"As result of Texas law?","start":174.296,"stop":175.719,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"As result Texas law, that is correct.","start":175.719,"stop":177.477,"duration":1.76}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) --","start":177.477,"stop":179.907,"duration":2.43}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no.","start":179.907,"stop":181.302,"duration":1.39},{"text":"She would get only her half of community property less one-half of the community debts and that would net out to be $111,000.","start":181.302,"stop":190.199,"duration":8.9},{"text":"She, in fact, elected to comply with the will and to allow the property to pass under the will.","start":190.199,"stop":195.123,"duration":4.92},{"text":"Under the will, she received one-third of his separate property which is worth $22,000 and kept one-third of the community property which is worth $85,000, which totaled $107,000.","start":195.123,"stop":210.578,"duration":15.46},{"text":"That is by electing to take under the will, she in fact received $4000 less than she already owned by virtue of her half interest in the community property.","start":210.578,"stop":222.434,"duration":11.86},{"text":"So, in order to receive $22,000 worth of the decedent's separate property, she had to sacrifice $26,000 worth of property that she owned in her own right.","start":222.434,"stop":235.284,"duration":12.85},{"text":"The question is whether --","start":235.284,"stop":235.984,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"That is -- that is half of the community property?","start":235.984,"stop":238.435,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, she kept --","start":238.435,"stop":238.87,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"26 --","start":238.87,"stop":239.909,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"-- she -- under the will, she kept at 30 of the property--","start":239.909,"stop":241.982,"duration":2.07}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":241.982,"stop":242.96,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"-- which is $85,000.","start":242.96,"stop":244.706,"duration":1.75},{"text":"Otherwise, she would have $111,000.","start":244.706,"stop":246.456,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":246.456,"stop":246.936,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the difference between (Voice Overlap)","start":246.936,"stop":247.146,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"-- there's been a third and a half of the community property","start":247.146,"stop":249.334,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"Which is $26,000.","start":249.334,"stop":250.941,"duration":1.61}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what happened to the debts?","start":250.941,"stop":254.725,"duration":3.78}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"The debts really don't enter in to this part of the case.","start":254.725,"stop":257.982,"duration":3.26},{"text":"That's really the second question and I will develop that separately.","start":257.982,"stop":262.255,"duration":4.27},{"text":"So, the question is whether the gift to the spouse of $22,000 worth of separate property only on condition that she give $26,000 worth of her property to the trust for the children qualifies for the marital deduction.","start":262.255,"stop":280.337,"duration":18.08},{"text":"The Court of Appeals held that it did over vigorous dissent by Judge Wisdom and I think on reflection, it's evident that has very drastic implications because what it means really is that a gift to anyone including remote decedents can be made to qualify to the marital deduction by the simple device of its first exchanging properties with the surviving wife -- surviving spouse.","start":280.337,"stop":306.64,"duration":26.3},{"text":"All its necessary is to precede that its positive provisions of the will with a provision giving the property to the wife on condition that she convey property of equal value in accordance with the remaining terms of the will.","start":306.64,"stop":319.912,"duration":13.27}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"But the purpose of the election I suppose is to give her a choice of one situation as more advantageous than the other.","start":319.912,"stop":329.112,"duration":9.2}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the election really amounts nothing more than offer made in the will, an offer that I will trade you $122,000 worth of separate my property --","start":329.112,"stop":338.474,"duration":9.36}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) position that all elections, widow's elections are --","start":338.474,"stop":342.308,"duration":3.83}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"No, not an election, not an election that is an election between two alternative ways of receiving property by descent i.e. between dower and a statutory right, knew of dower.","start":342.308,"stop":351.401,"duration":9.09},{"text":"This isn't that kind of election between two alternative kinds of inheritance.","start":351.401,"stop":356.635,"duration":5.23},{"text":"She owe -- under Texas law she independently owned one half of the community property, so she is conveying her owned property in exchange for his transfer to her under his will of a share of his separate property.","start":356.635,"stop":373.097,"duration":16.46}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"And that's not permissible?","start":373.097,"stop":375.064,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"It's permissible to do but the consequence cannot be that the estate is entitled to marital deduction.","start":375.064,"stop":383.457,"duration":8.39},{"text":"I hope to prove by giving the wife less than she must give to receive it because she has to give up $26,000 to receive the $22,000.","start":383.457,"stop":395.494,"duration":12.04},{"text":"Now, I think that would be clear enough even if the statute were silent on the question.","start":395.494,"stop":401.847,"duration":6.35},{"text":"In fact, I've --","start":401.847,"stop":402.628,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":402.628,"stop":405.562,"duration":2.93}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"The limitation on the marital deduction is 50% on just the gross estate.","start":405.562,"stop":410.164,"duration":4.6}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Of the gross?","start":410.164,"stop":411.057,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"But the full bequest would part of their argument, that limitation is not applicable here.","start":411.057,"stop":417.764,"duration":6.71},{"text":"So, anything which qualifies as a deductible bequest to the widow would be fully deducted.","start":417.764,"stop":425.528,"duration":7.76},{"text":"We don't reach the limitation in this case.","start":425.528,"stop":428.077,"duration":2.55}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"What if they were even trade?","start":428.077,"stop":430.349,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"They were even trade.","start":430.349,"stop":434.212,"duration":3.86},{"text":"They would amount in our view simply to a -- an exchange of properties not a gift of anything to the wife and it's only for gifts to the wife that you get a deduction.","start":434.212,"stop":443.86,"duration":9.65}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)?","start":443.86,"stop":445.646,"duration":1.79}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"A testamentary gift.","start":445.646,"stop":447.831,"duration":2.19},{"text":"I'd like to turn to the statute because I think quite surprisingly the statute addresses itself to the very question.","start":447.831,"stop":453.563,"duration":5.73}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":453.563,"stop":456.599,"duration":3.04}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":456.599,"stop":457.216,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":457.216,"stop":458.585,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":458.585,"stop":459.699,"duration":1.11},{"text":"As a matter of fact in these circumstances, the widow since she gave up more than she got, she would be liable for gift tax on the excess that she conveyed.","start":459.699,"stop":467.371,"duration":7.67}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Barnett, can either of these problems arise from the acceptance of the community property aspect?","start":467.371,"stop":472.061,"duration":4.69}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh yes, yes.","start":472.061,"stop":473.321,"duration":1.26},{"text":"This question is not at all dependent from a community property aspect.","start":473.321,"stop":478.851,"duration":5.53},{"text":"The -- exactly identical --","start":478.851,"stop":480.106,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Which one, do you mean the marital deduction?","start":480.106,"stop":481.318,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the question -- it's not a marital deduction question.","start":481.318,"stop":482.363,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but the other question which is the --","start":482.363,"stop":484.701,"duration":2.34}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"Is I think peculiar to community property.","start":484.701,"stop":485.808,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Peculiar?","start":485.808,"stop":486.769,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it is.","start":486.769,"stop":488.672,"duration":1.9},{"text":"Well, it depends on what implications you read in to the Court of Appeals' opinion.","start":488.672,"stop":491.707,"duration":3.03},{"text":"If you read it in a broadest way, you might find that applicable in common law analogies, but I don't think it really meant to hold anything that goes beyond in community property.","start":491.707,"stop":504.239,"duration":12.53},{"text":"Was I answering the question?","start":504.239,"stop":505.603,"duration":1.36},{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":505.603,"stop":507.102,"duration":1.5},{"text":"Let me go on to the --","start":507.102,"stop":509.115,"duration":2.01}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"When, I interrupted you, I think you said you're going to turn to statute.","start":509.115,"stop":512.447,"duration":3.33}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"The statute is set forth in our brief to page 26, Section 812 (e) (1) of the 1939 Code.","start":512.447,"stop":521.397,"duration":8.95},{"text":"Sub-section -- sub-paragraph (A) grants a deduction from gross estate, the so-called marital deduction for an amount equal to the value of any interest in property which passes or has passed from the descendent to a surviving spouse.","start":521.397,"stop":539.955,"duration":18.56},{"text":"Sub-paragraph (E) provides that in valuing the interest which passes to the surviving spouse for that purpose, where such interest or property isn't encumbered in any manner or where the surviving spouse incurs any obligation imposed by the descendent with respect to the passing of such interest, such encumbrance or obligation shall be taken into account in the same manner as if the amount of a gift to such spouse would be determined.","start":539.955,"stop":570.946,"duration":30.99},{"text":"Now, it seems to me that cannot be denied that the -- a requirement that the widow in order to receive the bequest convey property of her own to a third party is an obligation imposed by the descendent with respect to the passing of the interest.","start":570.946,"stop":587.541,"duration":16.6},{"text":"Now, the petitioners -- the respondents do challenge that, but I -- I don't see any basis for reading such a limitation into this language.","start":587.541,"stop":597.23,"duration":9.69},{"text":"Specific -- particularly is that true because all this provision does is to incorporate the general principles for determining the value of a gift to any particular donee and there's no reason why the corporation would incorporate only a part of those principles.","start":597.23,"stop":611.83,"duration":14.6},{"text":"This is simply a general reference to the general principle for determining the value of a gift.","start":611.83,"stop":616.675,"duration":4.84},{"text":"I'm indebted in fact to respondents referring in their brief at page 19, a part of the committee report that we did not set out which says as much.","start":616.675,"stop":627.088,"duration":10.41},{"text":"It says, \"Describes the purpose of this provision as providing for the application in determining the value of any interest in property passing to the surviving spouse of rules which are generally applicable in determining the net value of any gift or bequest.","start":627.088,"stop":642.199,"duration":15.11},{"text":"\" This is simply an incorporation of the rules otherwise generally applicable.","start":642.199,"stop":647.662,"duration":5.46},{"text":"Now, where those rules, the context in which we have to look for those rules is in the context where the identity of the donee is important because the statute asked not simply how much -- how you will determine the total amount of a gift made by the grantor?","start":647.662,"stop":666.585,"duration":18.92},{"text":"Here, since the descendent has died, he certainly has given to somebody everything he owned.","start":666.585,"stop":672.532,"duration":5.95},{"text":"What it asked is how you determine the amount of the gift to such spouse, to that particular donee and it's there I think that the Court of Appeals went astray and ignored that trade.","start":672.532,"stop":682.907,"duration":10.38},{"text":"Now, the context in which the identity of the donee is important, are many.","start":682.907,"stop":688.682,"duration":5.77},{"text":"For income tax purposes, the charitable contribution deduction depends upon whether the gift is to a charity.","start":688.682,"stop":695.738,"duration":7.06},{"text":"For gift tax purposes, the identity of the donee controls not only the charitable contribution deduction and the marital deduction but also whether -- the extent to which a -- the $3000 annual exclusion is available which is limited to $3000 of gifts to anyone donee whether the gift splitting privilege is available, whether the donee is or who is secondarily liable for the gift tax because the donee is liable for the gift tax if it isn't paid by the donor.","start":695.738,"stop":736.881,"duration":41.14},{"text":"Now -- so in all of those contexts, we do have a problem on identifying who the donee of what part of the gift is and that is the context that the estate tax statute refers to and I assert that in every such context, a gift, a transfer from A to B on condition that B make a transfer to C is a gift by A to C and not a gift to B. B is simply an intermediary who makes an exchange of properties.","start":736.881,"stop":767.275,"duration":30.39},{"text":"Now, I -- several examples I think will make that very clear.","start":767.275,"stop":770.696,"duration":3.42},{"text":"If I --if I give $10,000 to charity, one condition that the charity delivers a hundred shares of stock worth a $100 of shared to my son, no one would suggest that I am entitled to a charitable contribution deduction.","start":770.696,"stop":787.084,"duration":16.39},{"text":"On the other hand, if I give $10,000 to a stockbroker on condition that he convey the shares of stock to a charity, I would be entitled to the charitable contribution deduction.","start":787.084,"stop":797.82,"duration":10.74},{"text":"Likewise, if I asked the stockbroker to deliver the stock to my son, I think the stockbroker would be surprised to learn that he was a donee who is secondary liable to the gift tax.","start":797.82,"stop":806.996,"duration":9.18},{"text":"He might be even more pleasantly surprised when it dawns on him that since it was gift, he wouldn't have to report it for income tax purposes.","start":806.996,"stop":815.391,"duration":8.39},{"text":"Again, if I'd already given $3000 to my son so I couldn't take another annual exclusion for gift to him, I don't suppose I could claim one by showing that I never made a gift to the stockbroker.","start":815.391,"stop":825.989,"duration":10.6},{"text":"So, every --","start":825.989,"stop":826.138,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) the different -- that will be much narrower, you know technical question is whether or not that's the meaning of the statute, the wording of encumbrance's obligation means encumbrance on the part of either obligation than (Voice Overlap) --","start":826.138,"stop":843.738,"duration":17.6}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"No obligation imposed by the descendent with respect to the passing of interest.","start":843.738,"stop":848.042,"duration":4.3},{"text":"I have said and I think it is evident that --","start":848.042,"stop":851.191,"duration":3.15}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"This can be --","start":851.191,"stop":851.641,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"-- a requirement --","start":851.641,"stop":852.396,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it could be granted anywhere I suppose -- isn't that nub of it whether it's encumbrance on the property (Voice Overlap) --","start":852.396,"stop":858.596,"duration":6.2}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"And not -- not that we --","start":858.596,"stop":859.677,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Or whether (Voice Overlap) --","start":859.677,"stop":859.942,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it's an obligation imposed with respect to the passing of property.","start":859.942,"stop":863.041,"duration":3.1}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":863.041,"stop":864.22,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"And by my first answer literally, this is an obligation imposed, i.e., a requirement that in order to receive it, you must do something is an obligation imposed with respect to a passing of an interest.","start":864.22,"stop":876.079,"duration":11.86},{"text":"And secondly, that the community reports made clear that all this is, is a general reference to the general rules to determine the amount of a gift to a particular person.","start":876.079,"stop":886.549,"duration":10.47},{"text":"That's the only reason for this provision being there which confirms my reading of obligation is not meaning in its specific kind of obligation.","start":886.549,"stop":897.852,"duration":11.3},{"text":"The -- now, I think --","start":897.852,"stop":898.684,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"If -- if you're right on that of course, then you get clear understanding.","start":898.684,"stop":902.347,"duration":3.66}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, well, I think it's perfectly clear than any other context there's no gift from A to B but B is required to make a transfer to C as a condition of receiving the gift except to the extent that the transfer to B exceeds the transfer that he is require to make to C and I say that that provision of estate tax provision -- of the estate tax on a section specifically incorporates those general principles and that's why it is there.","start":902.347,"stop":930.363,"duration":28.02}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":930.363,"stop":945.053,"duration":14.69}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct, that is correct.","start":945.053,"stop":946.83,"duration":1.78},{"text":"Anything that -- that his will gives certain excess of what she is required to give the children would qualify for marital deduction.","start":946.83,"stop":953.632,"duration":6.8},{"text":"Since in this case, she had to give up more than she got to marital deduction and I -- that really is our case on the marital deduction question.","start":953.632,"stop":960.741,"duration":7.11},{"text":"I think it is as simple as that.","start":960.741,"stop":965.534,"duration":4.79},{"text":"The second question -- let me add the regulations are very specific on this question.","start":965.534,"stop":972.484,"duration":6.95},{"text":"They clearly -- they have example which is in this very case that submitted by respondent, submitted by the Court of Appeals respondent from (Inaudible) only by holding that regulation is invalid.","start":972.484,"stop":985.769,"duration":13.28},{"text":"The second question is whether the estate is entitled to a deduction for the share of the community debts that would otherwise be chargeable to the wife's half of the community property.","start":985.769,"stop":999.147,"duration":13.38},{"text":"Now, I say there's a similar question involving the administration expenses, but since the debts are much more important in amount and we -- both parties agreed to be controlled by the same principles, I would make the oral argument in terms of the debts but not specifically touch under administration expenses.","start":999.147,"stop":1018.328,"duration":19.18},{"text":"The community estate, which in Texas law, it has an independent existence from the husband and wife individually.","start":1018.328,"stop":1024.911,"duration":6.58},{"text":"The community estate had asset of $258,000 as I have said.","start":1024.911,"stop":1029.536,"duration":4.63},{"text":"It also had debts of $32,000 which consisted primarily of income taxes owing on community income.","start":1029.536,"stop":1039.823,"duration":10.29},{"text":"Now, only one-half of the community assets were includable in the decedent's estate admittedly and our argument is that only one-half of the community debts were deductable from it.","start":1039.823,"stop":1049.639,"duration":9.82},{"text":"Now the decedent's will, however written, contained a provision directing his executors to pay all of the community debts, not merely one half, out of his half of the community property because of that provision, the estate claims that it is entitled to deduction for all of the community debts.","start":1049.639,"stop":1069.483,"duration":19.84},{"text":"That is both which half allocable to his half and half allocable to her half and the Court of Appeals had held the claim again, Judge Wilson dissenting.","start":1069.483,"stop":1081.096,"duration":11.61},{"text":"Now, I would like to start the statute on this provision is at page 25 of our brief and it provides that there shall be deducted from the gross estate such amounts for claims against the estate as are allowable under the laws of the jurisdiction administering the estate -- the estate, and it's page 25 and that is controlling provision here, that's clause 3 is the one directly relevant.","start":1081.096,"stop":1121.049,"duration":39.95},{"text":"I'd like to (Inaudible) There's no disagreement at all, between the parties or with the courts below, that in the absence of the will provision, all that the estate could've been required to pay in order that it could've deducted would have been one half of the community debts.","start":1121.049,"stop":1137.495,"duration":16.45},{"text":"Under Texas law, the community debts or the primary obligation of the community and upon this dissolution, they're chargeable one-half against each share.","start":1137.495,"stop":1148.388,"duration":10.89},{"text":"The husband is the manager of the community is personally liable for community debts but the wife is not.","start":1148.388,"stop":1155.56,"duration":7.17},{"text":"But, as between him and the community, his liability is only secondary and if he pays the debts on his personal separate property, he's entitled to reimbursement from the community.","start":1155.56,"stop":1166.645,"duration":11.09},{"text":"Therefore, it is established from the Texas law then of the death of a husband, the probate court which typically administers both the entire community estate and his separate estate, the probate court may charge against the decedent's estate only one-half of the community debt and must charge the other half against the wife share of the community property.","start":1166.645,"stop":1188.882,"duration":22.24},{"text":"That's in the absence of the will.","start":1188.882,"stop":1191.471,"duration":2.59},{"text":"I want to emphasize, there's no disagreement about that.","start":1191.471,"stop":1194.251,"duration":2.78},{"text":"It's common ground that -- but for the will provision, the wife share evidence would not be claims against the estate which were deductible.","start":1194.251,"stop":1202.933,"duration":8.68},{"text":"It is only the effect of the will provision is an issue.","start":1202.933,"stop":1206.008,"duration":3.08},{"text":"And the question is, whether that direction in the will, the direction of will for the payment of the wife's share of the debts converts her share of the debts -- the share of the debts would otherwise be chargeable against her half of the property into claims against the estate and we say --","start":1206.008,"stop":1223.584,"duration":17.58}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"The Texas law, the Texas law (Inaudible)","start":1223.584,"stop":1229.513,"duration":5.93}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"Under Texas law, legacies, they are also enforceable.","start":1229.513,"stop":1232.516,"duration":3},{"text":"Any provision of the will which is a valid provision of the will is enforceable and it is quite --","start":1232.516,"stop":1235.959,"duration":3.44}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1235.959,"stop":1239.331,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"Precisely.","start":1239.331,"stop":1239.959,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- required the marital deduction?","start":1239.959,"stop":1241.382,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it would -- it would qualify generally for the marital deduction.","start":1241.382,"stop":1246.44,"duration":5.06},{"text":"In this case, it wouldn't qualify the marital deduction for the reason I've already discussed because she had to give up more than she got anyway.","start":1246.44,"stop":1258.032,"duration":11.59}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes but that's -- I don't see why that reaches these --","start":1258.032,"stop":1261.305,"duration":3.27}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":1261.305,"stop":1262.352,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- these debts, the --","start":1262.352,"stop":1265.008,"duration":2.66}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"There's a collateral aspect of this which I'd hope not to get in to at oral argument, still within our brief a long footnote here, on page 17 of our brief, note 17.","start":1265.008,"stop":1278.613,"duration":13.61},{"text":"Actually, you see the provision directing payment of all of the debts out of his half of the community property was also conditioned upon her election to take under the will.","start":1278.613,"stop":1289.259,"duration":10.65},{"text":"So she had to give up, the figures I've been using $26,000 and $22,000 would both be increased by the $16,000 worth of debts and it would amount really -- his assumption of her debts really would increase her interest in the community property, then she has to give up that much more in order to get his -- a share of his separate property. So, that would again work out.","start":1289.259,"stop":1313.704,"duration":24.44},{"text":"I don't want to try to persuade you to the figure is here, would again work out, she giving up more than she got.","start":1313.704,"stop":1319.094,"duration":5.39}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1319.094,"stop":1321.626,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that's on our first ground so we don't really have that problem here.","start":1321.626,"stop":1325.777,"duration":4.15},{"text":"Well, I agree but generally, a provision in a decedent's will pay to his wife's debts would qualify for marital deduction.","start":1325.777,"stop":1333.605,"duration":7.83},{"text":"Now, our argument on this question is again a very simple one.","start":1333.605,"stop":1339.845,"duration":6.24},{"text":"In our view, the very essence of the claim and the only reason why it's allowed as a deduction is that it is enforceable against the estate regardless of the testator's wishes and that therefore reduces the net value of the property over which she has testamentary power.","start":1339.845,"stop":1358.287,"duration":18.44},{"text":"And something that it is payable by the executors only because the decedent exercised his testamentary power to direct the payment is not a claim against his estate.","start":1358.287,"stop":1369.709,"duration":11.42},{"text":"It is, as Judge Wisdom described it, merely straight pecuniary legacy.","start":1369.709,"stop":1374.36,"duration":4.65},{"text":"There's no difference, we say, between a $1000 legacy to a beneficiary and the direction to the executors to pay a $1000 debt that would otherwise be the primary obligation of the beneficiary.","start":1374.36,"stop":1390.563,"duration":16.2},{"text":"In short, it's our position is that since without the will, he is staying within required to pay only one-half of the debts, only one-half of the debts were claimed against his estate enforceable against the estate and only one-half of the debts were deductible from the estate and for that reason, both in this issue and on the first, the judgment should be reversed.","start":1390.563,"stop":1412.344,"duration":21.78}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1412.344,"stop":1415.565,"duration":3.22}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I think that's common ground.","start":1415.565,"stop":1417.522,"duration":1.96},{"text":"I don't think (Inaudible)","start":1417.522,"stop":1420.652,"duration":3.13}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Sutton.","start":1420.652,"stop":1428.778,"duration":8.13}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and members of the Court, I think it is a misnomer to characterize the will here as a gift of property upon a condition that Mrs. Stapf permits her property to pass through the trustees.","start":1428.778,"stop":1455.932,"duration":27.15},{"text":"Actually, we have two, two entirely separate and different events or occurrences.","start":1455.932,"stop":1464.224,"duration":8.29},{"text":"One is a gift from Mr. Stapf or not a gift, a bequest to her in the will of a portion of his property.","start":1464.224,"stop":1477.765,"duration":13.54},{"text":"She is put to the election to take under the will or to take against it.","start":1477.765,"stop":1485.544,"duration":7.78},{"text":"She exercised that election at a later time not of course at the time that the debt but was exercised at a later time.","start":1485.544,"stop":1498.901,"duration":13.36},{"text":"When she did that, she unquestionably made a gift of a portion of her property to the trustees for the benefit of her children or their children.","start":1498.901,"stop":1512.52,"duration":13.62},{"text":"Now, --","start":1512.52,"stop":1513.102,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Sutton, she would've had that election whether or not the will had discussed her election which is a matter of state law and then --","start":1513.102,"stop":1522.413,"duration":9.31}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1522.413,"stop":1522.487,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"-- she has the statutory rights?","start":1522.487,"stop":1524.557,"duration":2.07}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Under the state law, the husband or the wife, as far as that's concerned, can dispose of only his or her one-half of the community property by will.","start":1524.557,"stop":1539.044,"duration":14.49},{"text":"The other half of the community property is vested absolutely in the surviving spouse, the absolute title.","start":1539.044,"stop":1548.14,"duration":9.1},{"text":"So, in a normal situation, a husband or wife will dispose of only their one-half of the property by will.","start":1548.14,"stop":1558.871,"duration":10.73}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1558.871,"stop":1559.519,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"But it is a recognized principle that by the marital deduction, a husband or wife, either as far as that goes, can dispose of both halves of the community with the consent of the surviving spouse.","start":1559.519,"stop":1577.329,"duration":17.81},{"text":"The surviving spouse is then put to an election whether to take under the will or to take against the will.","start":1577.329,"stop":1585.425,"duration":8.1}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if she takes against the will if I understand you correctly --","start":1585.425,"stop":1588.53,"duration":3.11}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"If she takes --","start":1588.53,"stop":1588.976,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"-- all she gets is her half of this community property --","start":1588.976,"stop":1591.646,"duration":2.67}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct, sir.","start":1591.646,"stop":1592.703,"duration":1.06},{"text":"She would have a --","start":1592.703,"stop":1593.646,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Which she -- which she would have whether or not there was a will --","start":1593.646,"stop":1598.219,"duration":4.57}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"That is right.","start":1598.219,"stop":1598.832,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"-- which is always her.","start":1598.832,"stop":1599.802,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"That is her, that's fully vested interest.","start":1599.802,"stop":1602.396,"duration":2.59}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1602.396,"stop":1603.613,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"So, now when she elected under -- to take under the will, she made a gift of her property or of her fully vested portion of the community property to trustees for the benefit of their children.","start":1603.613,"stop":1624.523,"duration":20.91},{"text":"There is no question about what that is a gift and that there's gift tax consequences attached to it, and Mrs. Stapf has never questioned or denied that.","start":1624.523,"stop":1637.561,"duration":13.04},{"text":"Now, further, the point of Texas law or community property law, in instances where a widow elects to take under the will and a portion of the community property passes to her, in this instance, a one-third of the gross estate passed to her.","start":1637.561,"stop":1668.781,"duration":31.22},{"text":"Now, that was the property as far as community property was concerned, didn't pass to her under the will but was satisfied out of her one-half of the community property.","start":1668.781,"stop":1685.333,"duration":16.55},{"text":"If I make myself clear, she had a one-half interest in the community property initially.","start":1685.333,"stop":1698.144,"duration":12.81},{"text":"Under the will, she was given one-third interest in the gross estate which would include a one-third interest in the community property.","start":1698.144,"stop":1709.706,"duration":11.56},{"text":"Now, under Texas law, under decisions that are cited in the brief and there is no argument with the Government counsel about the Texas law upon that point.","start":1709.706,"stop":1721.447,"duration":11.74},{"text":"The one-third part of the community property that she finally ended up with didn't pass to her under Mr. Stapf's will but was satisfied out of her one-half and so a consequence, she gave a difference.","start":1721.447,"stop":1742.26,"duration":20.81}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll recess now Mr. Sutton.","start":1742.26,"stop":1745.771,"duration":3.51}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - October 24, 1963","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren11/oral_argument_audio/14394","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 54, United States, Petitioner, versus Dorothy Anne Stapf and B. T. Ware, etcetera.","start":0,"stop":13.513,"duration":13.51},{"text":"Mr. Sutton, you may --","start":13.513,"stop":17.501,"duration":3.99}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, members of the Court.","start":17.501,"stop":23.441,"duration":5.94},{"text":"As I was pointing out yesterday, we have involved here two touchable transactions, I say, involved here.","start":23.441,"stop":34.055,"duration":10.61},{"text":"We only have one involved and that is the estate tax on the estate of Lowell Stapf.","start":34.055,"stop":42.523,"duration":8.47},{"text":"The other taxable event or transaction that will give rise to taxes would be the gift by Mrs. Stapf to the trustees of a portion of -- for community property as a result of her election.","start":42.523,"stop":62.521,"duration":20},{"text":"That would be subject to such gift taxes as -- or imposed by the gift tax statute.","start":62.521,"stop":70.245,"duration":7.72},{"text":"So -- but that is not what we are here concerned with, it's not involved in this case and it's not an issue.","start":70.245,"stop":79.619,"duration":9.37},{"text":"We have only the issue of the estate taxes in the estate of Lowell Stapf.","start":79.619,"stop":88.019,"duration":8.4},{"text":"Now, of course, prior to 1942 and since 1948, the community property States, only the one-half share of the community property of a decedent is included in his estate for estate tax purposes, that is the -- the share and part of the community property of the decedent.","start":88.019,"stop":119.878,"duration":31.86},{"text":"Of course, during the period from 1942 to 1948, the entire community property, both halves, was subject to a federal -- estate tax.","start":119.878,"stop":131.954,"duration":12.08},{"text":"Now, in 1948, the marital deduction provision was adopted to the remedy and the situation that existed and put all estates on a parity.","start":131.954,"stop":148.99,"duration":17.04},{"text":"In that, there would be only one-half of the property tax either in a community property State or in a non-community property State to the extent that the property passed from the deceased spouse to the surviving spouse.","start":148.99,"stop":171.86,"duration":22.87},{"text":"Now -- and that was put in by putting in the marital deduction.","start":171.86,"stop":178.833,"duration":6.97}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"It's free of tax?","start":178.833,"stop":180.85,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Beg your pardon?","start":180.85,"stop":181.449,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"Marital deduction is free?","start":181.449,"stop":183.184,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"It is deductible, yes.","start":183.184,"stop":184.694,"duration":1.51},{"text":"In determining the estate tax, it is deducted just like administration expenses or funeral expenses or debts and claims.","start":184.694,"stop":195.337,"duration":10.64},{"text":"It is deducted to the extent of one-half of the adjusted gross estate.","start":195.337,"stop":204.237,"duration":8.9},{"text":"Now, the adjusted gross estate, to determine that, you take the total estate both halves in the community, deduct from it all community property, makes other adjustments for administration expenses.","start":204.237,"stop":224.035,"duration":19.8},{"text":"And the substance of -- roughly, what you come out with, the adjusted gross estate is that -- is -- in a community property State, only the property that is a separate property of the spouse.","start":224.035,"stop":244.774,"duration":20.74},{"text":"Now, in a non-community property State, you do not have that -- you do not have that limitation.","start":244.774,"stop":254.937,"duration":10.16},{"text":"It's amounts to the same thing because it's one-half of the gross estate, adjusted gross estate that is the limit of the deduction.","start":254.937,"stop":269.518,"duration":14.58},{"text":"Now, that was adopted.","start":269.518,"stop":277.48,"duration":7.96},{"text":"The marital deduction was passed in 1948 to equalize the community property States and the non-community property States by allowing this deduction of one-half.","start":277.48,"stop":296.766,"duration":19.29},{"text":"The -- what we're concerned here with today is the value of the property that passed from Mr. Stapf to Mrs. Stapf.","start":296.766,"stop":313.662,"duration":16.9},{"text":"For a property to qualify for the marital deduction, there are several things that must occur.","start":313.662,"stop":322.676,"duration":9.01},{"text":"First, the property -- the -- or value which is to be deducted and qualified for the marital deduction, it must be included in the estate of the decedent.","start":322.676,"stop":335.073,"duration":12.4},{"text":"That's the first requirement.","start":335.073,"stop":337.201,"duration":2.13},{"text":"The second requirement is that the property must pass from the decedent to his surviving spouse.","start":337.201,"stop":346.994,"duration":9.79},{"text":"Of course, there are other limitations such as the terminable requirement but we're not concerned with that because the property that passed to Mrs. Stapf, passed to her absolutely -- excuse me.","start":346.994,"stop":365.258,"duration":18.26},{"text":"In Mr. Stapf's estate, he owned real property in the City of Amarillo, value that $65,000.","start":365.258,"stop":376.638,"duration":11.38},{"text":"He also owns some hand properties described in the will, his hand tools, value at $100.","start":376.638,"stop":387.444,"duration":10.81},{"text":"He owned one-half interest in community property of a total value of $258,000 that is, both halves of the community.","start":387.444,"stop":401.274,"duration":13.83},{"text":"Now, the hand tools passed out of the picture because they were -- it was subject of a special request.","start":401.274,"stop":410.469,"duration":9.19},{"text":"Then he left to Mrs. Stapf one-third of the gross estate, both separate property and community property and put her to an election to take under the will or not to take under the will.","start":410.469,"stop":427.466,"duration":17},{"text":"So, one-third interest in this real property valued at $65,000 passed to Mrs. Stapf under the will, that's the separate property.","start":427.466,"stop":441.116,"duration":13.65},{"text":"Additionally, she took or retained a one-third interest in the total community estate, both halves.","start":441.116,"stop":455.309,"duration":14.19},{"text":"Now, there is no question about the separate property being included in Mr. Stapf's estate and being subject to estate taxes.","start":455.309,"stop":468.355,"duration":13.05},{"text":"There is no question but what the one-third interest in this separate property passed to Mrs. Stapf.","start":468.355,"stop":478.682,"duration":10.33},{"text":"It passed to her absolutely, so you'll have the first two requirements under the gift tax -- under the marital deduction statute.","start":478.682,"stop":489.745,"duration":11.06},{"text":"Then you come to a question of determining how much is to be deducted in determining the estate that is subject to estate taxes.","start":489.745,"stop":506.695,"duration":16.95},{"text":"Now, we submit that the full $22,000 or one-third of the $65,000 is deductible under the statute.","start":506.695,"stop":526.777,"duration":20.08},{"text":"It's by virtue of a regulation of the Commissioner that it is claimed that the property so passing to Mrs. Stapf cannot be valued at its full value for the purpose of the deduction.","start":526.777,"stop":549.694,"duration":22.92}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"You concede that the regulation covers the facts of this case?","start":549.694,"stop":554.694,"duration":5}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":554.694,"stop":555.636,"duration":0.94},{"text":"We take the position of the regulation is invalid.","start":555.636,"stop":558.868,"duration":3.23},{"text":"It is --","start":558.868,"stop":559.818,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"I repeat my question.","start":559.818,"stop":561.221,"duration":1.4},{"text":"You concede that the regulation, that the words of the regulation cover the facts of this case?","start":561.221,"stop":566.435,"duration":5.21}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it -- it's designed and directed at the -- at this.","start":566.435,"stop":572.991,"duration":6.56},{"text":"The -- of course, the trial court and the Court of Appeals both held the regulation to be invalid and an extension beyond the statute.","start":572.991,"stop":584.818,"duration":11.83},{"text":"Now, turning -- turning to the -- the statute itself, 812 (e) (1) (E) (ii) is the part of the statute that refers to the valuation of the property that passes here.","start":584.818,"stop":619.343,"duration":34.52},{"text":"It says, \"Where -- where an interest or a property is incumbered or any manner -- in any manner or whether the surviving spouse incurs an obligation imposed by the decedent with the respect to the passing of such interest, such incumbrance or obligation shall be taken into the account in the same manner as if the amount of a gift to such spouse of such interest were being determined.\"","start":619.343,"stop":650.463,"duration":31.12},{"text":"Now, we have here a question of determining the amount that is passing.","start":650.463,"stop":658.245,"duration":7.78},{"text":"Mr. Barnett puts emphasis on the words to such spouse.","start":658.245,"stop":663.904,"duration":5.66},{"text":"But that is not the subject matter of the section of the statute.","start":663.904,"stop":670.401,"duration":6.5},{"text":"It is the amount that presses.","start":670.401,"stop":674.42,"duration":4.02},{"text":"Now, the regulation has a specific provision in it that deals with a community property estate that is section -- Regulation 81.47c.","start":674.42,"stop":697.709,"duration":23.29},{"text":"After referring to an interest that is subject to a mortgage or other incumbrance, they say the passing of a property interest subject to the imposition of an obligation by the decedent does not include a bequest, devise, or transfer in lieu of bower, curtesy, or other statutory estate created in lieu of dower or curtesy or other marital rights in the decedent property or estate.","start":697.709,"stop":726.447,"duration":28.74},{"text":"Then, specifically directed out of community property State, the regulation says, \"The passing of a property interest subject to the imposition of an obligation by the decedent does not include a bequest in lieu of the interest of his surviving spouse under the community property laws unless such interest was immediately deprived of the decedent's death a mere expectancy.","start":726.447,"stop":764.14,"duration":37.69},{"text":"Now, that is -- that regulation is directed particularly toward community property States.","start":764.14,"stop":774.564,"duration":10.42},{"text":"Under its language, it would apply, as far as the language is concern, only in a community property State.","start":774.564,"stop":782.37,"duration":7.81},{"text":"In answer to the question that was asked yesterday as to whether or not this problem could rise in a non-community property State, I'll say that it cannot arise except where the surviving spouse has property of her own over which she has control except for the property of her own and can dispose of it by will gift for the other one.","start":782.37,"stop":810.149,"duration":27.78},{"text":"As in other words, that's -- it would be something that would occur in other States but only where the wife has property of her own is subject to her control.","start":810.149,"stop":823.024,"duration":12.88},{"text":"Now, the question here is the amount of the property that passes and it is to be determined as if a gift was being made -- being valued for gift purposes.","start":823.024,"stop":842.903,"duration":19.88},{"text":"Now, the Commissioner takes the position that what Mrs. Stapf gave to her children should be offset against what she received in determining the benefit from her.","start":842.903,"stop":865.085,"duration":22.18},{"text":"Now, there are two things wrong with that.","start":865.085,"stop":869.699,"duration":4.61},{"text":"In the first place, if that is allowed to zero out the value of the property that passed under the estate tax, you're going to be subjecting that property to two estate taxes, one, when Mr. Stapf died and the other, when Mrs. Stapf dies.","start":869.699,"stop":896.65,"duration":26.95},{"text":"That is contrary to the expressed purpose and intent of the adoption of the marital deduction provision.","start":896.65,"stop":906.633,"duration":9.98},{"text":"So, if -- if the Government's position is maintained, you'll be taxing this property, this separate property of Mr. Stapf.","start":906.633,"stop":919.788,"duration":13.15},{"text":"You'll be taxing it for estate tax purposes twice.","start":919.788,"stop":923.227,"duration":3.44},{"text":"Once in Mr. Stapf's estate and again, when Mrs. Stapf dies.","start":923.227,"stop":929.48,"duration":6.25},{"text":"There is one other fault and trouble with that.","start":929.48,"stop":938.094,"duration":8.61},{"text":"Actually, what she would be -- what the Government is saying should be done is that a tax should be levied upon what Mrs. Stapf gives to her children.","start":938.094,"stop":952.59,"duration":14.5},{"text":"Now, if that is subject to any tax at all, and we don't deny that it is that it's a gift and it's subject to such gift taxes as are applicable to it.","start":952.59,"stop":964.162,"duration":11.57},{"text":"Alright.","start":964.162,"stop":966.319,"duration":2.16},{"text":"If it is a taxable gift, it is taxable at gift tax rates.","start":966.319,"stop":972.869,"duration":6.55},{"text":"Yet, if you take that value and put it over in the estate, you're going to be taxing that gift, not at gift tax rates but at estate tax rates and subjecting it not to a gift tax but subjecting it to estate tax in Mr. Stapf's estate.","start":972.869,"stop":994.96,"duration":22.09},{"text":"Contrary, we submit to the clear intent purpose and language of the marital deduction provision.","start":994.96,"stop":1006.409,"duration":11.45}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Is the relationship of the gift tax rates to the estate tax rates was a two-third?","start":1006.409,"stop":1012.544,"duration":6.13}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"No, well, it's substantially less so it would be --","start":1012.544,"stop":1015.098,"duration":2.55}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Around about two -- two-thirds although it's yours, isn't it?","start":1015.098,"stop":1018.384,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1018.384,"stop":1019.843,"duration":1.46},{"text":"In the lower brackets I believe it's more than -- I mean --","start":1019.843,"stop":1022.253,"duration":2.41}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"More -- more of a difference, is that it?","start":1022.253,"stop":1023.43,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"More difference in the lower brackets but in the higher brackets it is --","start":1023.43,"stop":1026.976,"duration":3.55}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"All the way to the gift tax rates are lower, of course.","start":1026.976,"stop":1030.41,"duration":3.43}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1030.41,"stop":1033.976,"duration":3.57},{"text":"Now, the -- the statute says that you're going to tax this and determine the value as if in the same manner, as if the amount of a gift to such federal of -- of an interest was being (Inaudible).","start":1033.976,"stop":1063.395,"duration":29.42},{"text":"Now, when you go to the value of the property for gift tax passing from a donor to a donee, you tax that at its market value.","start":1063.395,"stop":1079.514,"duration":16.12},{"text":"It's full value.","start":1079.514,"stop":1082.137,"duration":2.62},{"text":"Now, of course, there is a provision in the gift tax statute that authorizes if it's purchased for a bona fide consideration, it's taxed only to the extent of the above the amount for which it has given.","start":1082.137,"stop":1102.334,"duration":20.2},{"text":"Now, this Court decided some years ago in the Wemyss case, I take it that's the way you pronounce it, W-E-M-Y-S-S, that a -- in valuing a gift from a donor to another person, that only a consideration moving back to the donor and measured in money or money's worth, was to be deducted.","start":1102.334,"stop":1141.607,"duration":39.27},{"text":"In that instance, in that instance, the donor gave to his intended bride certain stocks in consideration of her agreement to marry.","start":1141.607,"stop":1162.561,"duration":20.95},{"text":"As a result of her marriage, she gave up a beneficial interest in a trust that had been created for her by her former husband.","start":1162.561,"stop":1177.637,"duration":15.08},{"text":"So, when they got ready to determine the value of the gift from the husband to his intended bride, it was the taxpayer's contention that what she gave up should be offset against what she received to determine the value of the gift.","start":1177.637,"stop":1199.172,"duration":21.54},{"text":"But this Court held that that was not the situation.","start":1199.172,"stop":1203.368,"duration":4.2},{"text":"That it had to be a consideration passing to the donor and measured in money or money's worth.","start":1203.368,"stop":1213.08,"duration":9.71},{"text":"And therefore, the value of the stock that passed from the donor to his intended bride was to be valued at its full market value.","start":1213.08,"stop":1222.967,"duration":9.89},{"text":"Now, the Court held that the mere deposition to the donee didn't satisfy the requirements of the gift statute.","start":1222.967,"stop":1233.394,"duration":10.43},{"text":"Now, that is the statute obviously that Congress is referring to in the adoption of the marital deduction provision and the provision where it says that it shall be determined as if a gift was and if an amount of the gift was being determined.","start":1233.394,"stop":1251.486,"duration":18.09},{"text":"That was the basis of the holding of the trial court and that was the basis to the holding of the Court of Civil Appeals in this case relying upon the Wemyss case.","start":1251.486,"stop":1265.796,"duration":14.31},{"text":"Now, we have that kind of situation here because when Mrs. Stapf elected to take under the will and therefore, surrendered a part of her property to the trustees for the benefit of her children, there was nothing that passed from her back to the donor or -- or the testator in this case, Mr. Stapf.","start":1265.796,"stop":1302.294,"duration":36.5},{"text":"It was a benefit that passed from her to a third party and not a consideration that moved from her back to the donor.","start":1302.294,"stop":1313.561,"duration":11.27},{"text":"So, the Wemyss case would certainly require the valuation of the interest that passed from Mr. Stapf to Mrs. Stapf under the will at its full market value.","start":1313.561,"stop":1332.591,"duration":19.03},{"text":"That's the only question we have is how to value this property of the passed.","start":1332.591,"stop":1337.98,"duration":5.39},{"text":"There's no question about what it passed and qualifies in every other respect for the marital deduction.","start":1337.98,"stop":1344.849,"duration":6.87},{"text":"Now, when Mrs. Stapf elected to take under the will, her half of the community property did not go back to or become a part of the estate of Mr. Stapf or subject to estate taxes in his estate for gift tax purposes.","start":1344.849,"stop":1365.864,"duration":21.02},{"text":"There is a GCM ruling on that that has been in effect for many years that where a widow is put to an election, her property, her half of the community does not become a part of the community of the decedent for estate tax purposes.","start":1365.864,"stop":1387.629,"duration":21.76},{"text":"So, that property passed to -- passed to third parties and it's not included into the estate -- estate tax purposes.","start":1387.629,"stop":1402.413,"duration":14.78},{"text":"Now, the Government takes the position that the election was an obligation, I mean the provision in the will requiring Mrs. Stapf to exercise an election, was an obligation imposed upon by the decedent with respect to the passing of this interest under the statute.","start":1402.413,"stop":1432.822,"duration":30.41},{"text":"We submit that the word \"obligation\", as there used, refers to an obligation in the nature of a -- in the incumbrance or a charge upon the specific property that passes under the will.","start":1432.822,"stop":1453.883,"duration":21.06},{"text":"We think that the Senate Report and the House Report explaining this provision makes that clear that it is an obligation or a charge that is on the property itself.","start":1453.883,"stop":1477.822,"duration":23.94},{"text":"And since this is not a charge upon this particular property, it is not an obligation within the meaning of the statute.","start":1477.822,"stop":1494.932,"duration":17.11},{"text":"We think that the Senate Report upon -- upon that point makes it clear.","start":1494.932,"stop":1505.002,"duration":10.07},{"text":"And the trial court concurred with us in that view.","start":1505.002,"stop":1511.792,"duration":6.79},{"text":"The Court of Appeals didn't reach the question on whether or not the obligation was in -- in the nature of a charge upon the specific property, because the Court of Appeals concluded that under the direction in the statute that the amount of the gift be determined as if a -- I mean amount of the property passing, qualifying for the marital deduction, would be determined as if a gift were being made.","start":1511.792,"stop":1555.787,"duration":44},{"text":"And that therefore, they did not find it necessary to reach and decide the question of the obligation because they thought the question was concluded and decided by the Wemyss case.","start":1555.787,"stop":1580.363,"duration":24.58},{"text":"The Wemyss case has been followed and report that we're contending for here, is illustrated in some tax court decisions.","start":1580.363,"stop":1598.013,"duration":17.65},{"text":"The Bartman case, it has a situation parallel to what we have involved.","start":1598.013,"stop":1607.452,"duration":9.44},{"text":"Now, in the petition for writ of certiorari and in the brief, counsel for the petitioner puts emphasis upon what he says would be a loss of revenue if the opinion of the Court's -- Circuit Court of Appeals is followed.","start":1607.452,"stop":1643.797,"duration":36.35},{"text":"The Circuit Court recognized that under the decision in Segal versus Commissioner by one of the Circuit Court of Appeals that in valuing the gift for gift tax purposes that passed from Mrs. Stapf to the children that she was entitled to deduct the amount that she gave up being her one-sixth part of the community estate or the difference between one-third and one-half which she would've had, had she elected to take against the will.","start":1643.797,"stop":1697.522,"duration":53.72},{"text":"If that be true and the Segal case had been followed in a number of several other cases by the tax court, even if that be true, that is no reason for imposing an estate tax where the statute does not impose estate tax.","start":1697.522,"stop":1727.416,"duration":29.89}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"You don't -- you don't suggest that the result here is to put both (Inaudible) tax.","start":1727.416,"stop":1733.37,"duration":5.95}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"I didn't understand.","start":1733.37,"stop":1735.574,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"You do not suggest that the result here is to put both in the estate and -- and the gift tax on any amount of money.","start":1735.574,"stop":1743.862,"duration":8.29}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, as --","start":1743.862,"stop":1744.576,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean on the same money.","start":1744.576,"stop":1748.232,"duration":3.66}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I -- you got two --","start":1748.232,"stop":1749.007,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Or neither be one of the others, you object to putting the higher estate tax on the amount to pass in the wife to the trust rather than a gift tax.","start":1749.007,"stop":1757.797,"duration":8.79}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't think that's part of the estate.","start":1757.797,"stop":1759.976,"duration":2.18},{"text":"No, sir.","start":1759.976,"stop":1760.692,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1760.692,"stop":1760.933,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":1760.933,"stop":1762.116,"duration":1.18},{"text":"No.","start":1762.116,"stop":1762.777,"duration":0.66},{"text":"I -- I --","start":1762.777,"stop":1762.926,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But there won't be both -- there won't be both taxes under $26,000.","start":1762.926,"stop":1767.614,"duration":4.69}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"No, there won't be both taxes, there will be -- there will be an estate tax on --","start":1767.614,"stop":1772.417,"duration":4.8}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand.","start":1772.417,"stop":1772.594,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"-- Mr. Stapf's estate --","start":1772.594,"stop":1773.977,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand.","start":1773.977,"stop":1774.557,"duration":0.58},{"text":"On the 22 --","start":1774.557,"stop":1775.268,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"-- which is --","start":1775.268,"stop":1775.953,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- on the $22,000 that she received --","start":1775.953,"stop":1780.095,"duration":4.14}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it will be deducted under the marital deduction and there will be no estate tax paid in his estate.","start":1780.095,"stop":1786.041,"duration":5.95},{"text":"But when she does, that property will still be in her estate, assuming she had disposed of it and it will be subject to estate tax at that time.","start":1786.041,"stop":1795.494,"duration":9.45}]},{"speakerName":"Arthur J. Goldberg","textObjs":[{"text":"Counsel, do you assume that the property (Inaudible)","start":1795.494,"stop":1801.344,"duration":5.85}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course, of course.","start":1801.344,"stop":1803.211,"duration":1.87},{"text":"I think the -- that assumption is made in the marital deduction and the whole theory of it is to put it in two piles and tax half of it in the first estate.","start":1803.211,"stop":1818.032,"duration":14.82},{"text":"And then if anything is left, tax it in the -- in the second estate.","start":1818.032,"stop":1823.576,"duration":5.54},{"text":"No, I -- I -- that is just an assumption, of course, if you -- for me, necessary to there, of course.","start":1823.576,"stop":1831.556,"duration":7.98},{"text":"But it will be subject to a one -- it will be subject to one estate tax, that property and not two which would be the situation if the Government's position is sustained.","start":1831.556,"stop":1848.377,"duration":16.82},{"text":"Now, whatever -- whatever are the tax consequences for gift taxes and how much gift taxes Mrs. Stapf owes on her gift is, as I say, another matter, it's not here involved.","start":1848.377,"stop":1872.822,"duration":24.44},{"text":"We have here the valuation of the property passing from Mr. Stapf's estate.","start":1872.822,"stop":1881.576,"duration":8.75},{"text":"It qualifies in every way for the marital deduction.","start":1881.576,"stop":1884.962,"duration":3.39},{"text":"In that, it is a part of his estate and it passed from him to her the value -- to be valued as if a gift were being made and it's not the benefit to the donee but it is the amount of the gift that passes.","start":1884.962,"stop":1905.451,"duration":20.49},{"text":"The Wemyss case, we think, requires that this property valued -- be valued at its full value.","start":1905.451,"stop":1915.965,"duration":10.51},{"text":"Now, turning to the question of the deductibility of the debts and expenses of administration, the estate tax statute allows as deductions funeral expenses, administration expenses and claims against the estate as or allowed by the laws of the jurisdiction under which the estate is being administered.","start":1915.965,"stop":1956.449,"duration":40.48},{"text":"Now, under such a statute, you are not going to get uniformity in deductions because the deductions are determined by the state laws.","start":1956.449,"stop":1972.415,"duration":15.97},{"text":"So you're going to have a -- a divergence.","start":1972.415,"stop":1976.448,"duration":4.03},{"text":"We have cited in our brief a number of instances in community property States where funeral expenses are -- or administration expenses are allowed in the -- in -- entirely in some States and in others, only one-half.","start":1976.448,"stop":1995.697,"duration":19.25},{"text":"So, you don't get uniformity and it's not to be expected in deductions in the federal -- estate tax because of the difference of the different state law.","start":1995.697,"stop":2011.36,"duration":15.66},{"text":"Now, in Texas, in the absence of a will provision, only one-half of the administration expenses in a community property -- in a community estate are deducted in the, as I say, in the absence of a will provision.","start":2011.36,"stop":2037.281,"duration":25.92},{"text":"Now, will provisions whereby a decedent assumes all of the expenses, all of the funeral charges are valid and have been recognized as making those expenses deductible or claims, deductible in their entirety where the will so provides.","start":2037.281,"stop":2067.666,"duration":30.39},{"text":"That's been holding at least in the couple of tax court cases and those are the only cases that have been able to find on it is two tax court cases holding, except in the Court of Appeals, I believe it's for the Ninth Circuit, Lang versus Commissioner recognizes the right, although they didn't there apply it because the -- that's -- didn't qualified under other provisions of the statute that a will provision can change the debts and administration expenses from being charged partly to the -- to the survivor and partly to the decedent and can be assumed by the decedent in his will.","start":2067.666,"stop":2125.478,"duration":57.81}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"What was his reaction to -- to pay her share of the administration expenses anymore than the legacy to her?","start":2125.478,"stop":2135.3,"duration":9.82}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"We say that he is -- it -- it is certainly a legacy.","start":2135.3,"stop":2140.837,"duration":5.54},{"text":"It is certainly a legacy to her, it is a bequest to her but it is a provision that is authorized by the -- by Texas, recognized as a right in Texas.","start":2140.837,"stop":2156.783,"duration":15.95},{"text":"And therefore, it is a deductible expense that is chargeable against the estate in Texas and the statute says, \"Such debts and claims and expenses as are allowed by the laws of the jurisdiction.","start":2156.783,"stop":2176.751,"duration":19.97},{"text":"Federal statute says that it'll be in accordance to that.","start":2176.751,"stop":2179.68,"duration":2.93},{"text":"The laws of the jurisdiction in Texas allow that deduction where there is will provision, we say we fit within the statute.","start":2179.68,"stop":2187.944,"duration":8.26},{"text":"It is.","start":2187.944,"stop":2189.918,"duration":1.97},{"text":"Yes, sir, it is a -- additional bequest or benefit to her and as a legacy would certainly qualify for the marital deduction to --","start":2189.918,"stop":2203.668,"duration":13.75}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Isn't it --","start":2203.668,"stop":2204.546,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2204.546,"stop":2204.993,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- but wasn't this the same type of a -- of a so-called legacy to the wife as these other amounts that you out pay your debts if you'll give an equal amount to somebody else?","start":2204.993,"stop":2220.267,"duration":15.27}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I wouldn't qualify just that way.","start":2220.267,"stop":2222.985,"duration":2.72},{"text":"It --","start":2222.985,"stop":2224.351,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, otherwise, he wouldn't --","start":2224.351,"stop":2224.551,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"-- you say I will pay it -- I --","start":2224.551,"stop":2226.09,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- he wouldn't have as much to give -- she wouldn't have as much of her half in the community property left if -- if she'd had to pay her own --","start":2226.09,"stop":2234.408,"duration":8.32}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct.","start":2234.408,"stop":2234.97,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the same --","start":2234.97,"stop":2235.139,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct.","start":2235.139,"stop":2235.601,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the exact -- exactly the same amount.","start":2235.601,"stop":2239.25,"duration":3.65},{"text":"She would have more -- she would have left -- she would have had more of her separate proper or her half of the community property to give away if the estate hadn't paid her debts, so it seems to me, it's sort of a washout.","start":2239.25,"stop":2255.808,"duration":16.56}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't think it is a washout in -- when he assumes the indebtedness --","start":2255.808,"stop":2263.494,"duration":7.69}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Sure, he says, \"I'll pay your debt --","start":2263.494,"stop":2263.792,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"-- maybe equalizing --","start":2263.792,"stop":2263.925,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- I'll pay your debt if you'll give the same amount to -- to the children, in effect.\"","start":2263.925,"stop":2271.685,"duration":7.76}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"In the overall -- in the overall --","start":2271.685,"stop":2273.081,"duration":1.4}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there an economic effect though?","start":2273.081,"stop":2276.606,"duration":3.53}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if you wish to qualify it in that manner, it could be in a sense -- that's true.","start":2276.606,"stop":2285.975,"duration":9.37},{"text":"It is true that she would've had $16,000 less had -- had she -- had there not been any provision in the will (Inaudible).","start":2285.975,"stop":2295.567,"duration":9.59}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"So $16,000 more went to the children, I understand, if the estate hadn't paid her half of the year.","start":2295.567,"stop":2302.393,"duration":6.83}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, of course, whatever went to the children was more --","start":2302.393,"stop":2306.386,"duration":3.99}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Or went to the trust.","start":2306.386,"stop":2307.084,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"-- than would have gone to the children had he disposed of only his one-half interest.","start":2307.084,"stop":2313.679,"duration":6.6}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I understand that but --","start":2313.679,"stop":2316.115,"duration":2.44}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"So it's --","start":2316.115,"stop":2317.175,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it will only be irrelevant here.","start":2317.175,"stop":2321.007,"duration":3.83}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"He -- by -- undertakes his law, he can dispose of his separate property by his will and he could dispose of his one-half interest, unless his wife elects to permit him to dispose of the entire community which this will did.","start":2321.007,"stop":2339.52,"duration":18.51},{"text":"And in any sense, in any sense that is -- what you asked is certainly true.","start":2339.52,"stop":2347.335,"duration":7.82},{"text":"Whatever the children got, they got $16,000 more than -- had she elected to take against the will and kept her own money and dispose of it as she wanted to at a later term.","start":2347.335,"stop":2361.398,"duration":14.06},{"text":"That is correct.","start":2361.398,"stop":2362.161,"duration":0.76},{"text":"The children got -- got more by her election.","start":2362.161,"stop":2368.31,"duration":6.15},{"text":"Certainly, she ended up, she ended up here with less.","start":2368.31,"stop":2373.529,"duration":5.22}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"If her husband -- if her husband pays all the community debts, can he get the contribution from the spouse?","start":2373.529,"stop":2380.519,"duration":6.99}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, he has the right of contribution.","start":2380.519,"stop":2382.715,"duration":2.2},{"text":"There is no personal liability upon the wife and the husband and his estate is personally liable for the debts and obligations and suit maybe maintained against him and not against the -- the widow for -- in satisfaction of the debts.","start":2382.715,"stop":2406.253,"duration":23.54},{"text":"Now --","start":2406.253,"stop":2406.977,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But he need -- but his estate need not pay all the community debts.","start":2406.977,"stop":2413.616,"duration":6.64}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, his -- his estate is charged with all community debts but he has a right to reimburse it against --","start":2413.616,"stop":2418.068,"duration":4.45}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- that's --","start":2418.068,"stop":2418.122,"duration":0.05}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"-- his wife, yes.","start":2418.122,"stop":2420.548,"duration":2.43},{"text":"He has -- he has a right of reimbursement.","start":2420.548,"stop":2423.887,"duration":3.34},{"text":"Third parties have no claim against her but he has -- his statement has a right of reimbursement, correct.","start":2423.887,"stop":2430.092,"duration":6.2}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) as a legacy, do you agree with Mr. Barnett that notwithstanding that would be entitled to marital reduction has nothing more due by way of a deduction here because of the -- the wife, as I understand his contention, the wife, by making the election, still lost more than she would've gained by that legacy.","start":2430.092,"stop":2462.672,"duration":32.58}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"How --","start":2462.672,"stop":2463.021,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't understand the mathematics of that.","start":2463.021,"stop":2465.129,"duration":2.11},{"text":"I've examined Mr. Barnett's brief, I still don't understand it and I'd like to know whether you're in agreement with his view that this is --","start":2465.129,"stop":2473.443,"duration":8.31}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"I will agree with --","start":2473.443,"stop":2474.157,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- washed out.","start":2474.157,"stop":2475.166,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"-- I will agree with Mr. Barnett on that if these debts are not entitled to be deducted as debts and claims.","start":2475.166,"stop":2488.787,"duration":13.62},{"text":"And they are in -- to be considered only as a pecuniary bequest.","start":2488.787,"stop":2493.098,"duration":4.31}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2493.098,"stop":2493.912,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"I agree that that qualifies for the marital deduction.","start":2493.912,"stop":2497.391,"duration":3.48}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright, but he says --","start":2497.391,"stop":2498.364,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, he goes -- that's -- that's far as I agree with.","start":2498.364,"stop":2502.036,"duration":3.67}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright.","start":2502.036,"stop":2503.587,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"He says, from that point on, that there is no marital deduction because you ought to zero out the value of this property because she gave other property and she ended up with a net benefit of less than what she received.","start":2503.587,"stop":2528.232,"duration":24.64}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, that's --","start":2528.232,"stop":2528.477,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, of course, the mathematics wouldn't quite work out -- wouldn't quite work out.","start":2528.477,"stop":2536.953,"duration":8.48},{"text":"I -- I don't believe because she would actually benefit by $16,000, an additional benefit and what she -- of course, Mr. Barnett, gave up --","start":2536.953,"stop":2555.955,"duration":19}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":2555.955,"stop":2556.263,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"-- is the difference between a one-sixth and a -- and a -- I mean, a one-third and a one-half of her community property.","start":2556.263,"stop":2564.488,"duration":8.22}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, it would be --","start":2564.488,"stop":2564.974,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"So I think it's a --","start":2564.974,"stop":2565.52,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it would be help for me, at least, perhaps, the other members of the Court wouldn't object that you could make the Government or at least to both of you, you can agree on it, make the deductions as -- because I don't -- I cannot yet understand why, from a mathematical standpoint, granted that this is subject to the marital deduction, it doesn't result in the estate getting an additional deduction.","start":2565.52,"stop":2593.1,"duration":27.58}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"I certainly agree with that and --","start":2593.1,"stop":2595.942,"duration":2.84}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I can't -- I'd like to hold the mathematics, that's all.","start":2595.942,"stop":2599.054,"duration":3.11},{"text":"That the --","start":2599.054,"stop":2599.156,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright.","start":2599.156,"stop":2599.669,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the Government or you or somebody could give us some mathematics (Inaudible) need.","start":2599.669,"stop":2606.154,"duration":6.49}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, would it be permissible for us to write you on that?","start":2606.154,"stop":2611.478,"duration":5.32}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, with the permission of the Chief Justice.","start":2611.478,"stop":2613.425,"duration":1.95}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, you may do that.","start":2613.425,"stop":2617.808,"duration":4.38}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"To explain the mathematics and for -- instead trying to go through with that at this point.","start":2617.808,"stop":2622.315,"duration":4.51}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2622.315,"stop":2627.445,"duration":5.13}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, the point here is upon the -- the marital -- on these debts and claims.","start":2627.445,"stop":2657.266,"duration":29.82},{"text":"The Court of Appeals did not hope that all debts should be deducted from estate by a virtue of the provision in the will, I mean, it should be deducted in the determining estate taxes by a virtue of provision in the will, for the reason that the statute, authorizing these deductions, says, with respect to claim, that it maybe deducted only with respect to the -- the -- where there is a consideration in money or money's worth.","start":2657.266,"stop":2707.821,"duration":50.55},{"text":"Now, the debts and claims in this instance are in the main if not totally debts that arose by operation of law.","start":2707.821,"stop":2723.824,"duration":16},{"text":"Now, a claim to be deducted has to be a claim that is based upon a -- and based upon a promise, can be deducted only to the extent that the consideration was received in adequate consideration.","start":2723.824,"stop":2745.47,"duration":21.65},{"text":"Therefore, where you have a community debt, you would only deduct one-half of it under this statute even under our position as -- and under the holding of the Court of Appeals because a community debt is chargeable to equal -- to each half of the community and so you would only include one-half of the community property or interest in that estate of the decedent that first died and so you would only deduct and charge -- I mean, you would deduct only one-half of the -- of the debts that are founded upon a promise and consideration.","start":2745.47,"stop":2805.834,"duration":60.36},{"text":"The -- that fact alone will prevent there being the opportunity for a person as to -- to manipulate the debts and liabilities to where it would zero out property or as far as estate tax purpose is concerned.","start":2805.834,"stop":2836.654,"duration":30.82},{"text":"That was a matter of concern to Judge Wisdom in his dissenting opinion that illustrates -- it was used in the petition for certiorari.","start":2836.654,"stop":2850.882,"duration":14.23},{"text":"But when you read the Circuit Court's opinion in light of the consideration required, the situation or illustration given where a person owned a million dollars and went out and bargain another million dollars and then took the $200,000 or two million dollars and bought two million dollars worth of stock and then the husband assumed all of the indebtedness and this property supposed to -- to pass tax free, it doesn't -- it doesn't work out that way, the mathematics doesn't work out that way because only one-half of that debt would be deductible in the husband's estate, so you would have -- you have half a million dollars -- they originally had a million dollars from \"inde\" and they bought another million dollar worth of stock, wait a minute, they had bought two million dollars worth of stock, so there'd be a million dollars under this example that would subject to tax in the estate and you would have a deduction of only half of the indebtedness or $500,000 and so, there is not the chance of tax avoidance that is feared in the deduction of the statute.","start":2850.882,"stop":2949.541,"duration":98.66},{"text":"Now, in conclusion, let me say on the marital deduction that we have only the amount of the property that passes, the only question of valuation.","start":2949.541,"stop":2975.532,"duration":25.99},{"text":"Government counsel says that that just got a zero value simply because she gave away the property.","start":2975.532,"stop":2983.442,"duration":7.91},{"text":"Now, we are not concerned here with the benefit to her but the question is what are we going to tax in Mr. Stapf's estate?","start":2983.442,"stop":2998.733,"duration":15.29}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"If the -- if the martial deduction that her estate is -- is -- that is solidly increased by --","start":2998.733,"stop":3011.501,"duration":12.77}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir, it is solidly increased.","start":3011.501,"stop":3012.883,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And if X -- X dollars comes in on condition that Y -- X dollars goes out, she's automatically -- this isn't -- this doesn't --","start":3012.883,"stop":3026.843,"duration":13.96}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"This X dollar --","start":3026.843,"stop":3027.811,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- this doesn't comport with the idea -- with the assumption that this -- this property will remain in her estate.","start":3027.811,"stop":3036.93,"duration":9.12}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"These X dollars as going out of her estate is going out of her property over which she has control --","start":3036.93,"stop":3045.241,"duration":8.31}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":3045.241,"stop":3045.26,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and not the property --","start":3045.26,"stop":3046.378,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":3046.378,"stop":3046.827,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that comes from --","start":3046.827,"stop":3047.988,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":3047.988,"stop":3048.021,"duration":0.03}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"-- comes from him.","start":3048.021,"stop":3050.003,"duration":1.98}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I agree with you.","start":3050.003,"stop":3050.311,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, if -- if Mr. Stapf had said, \"I'm going to give you my one-third interest in these lots down here but you go mortgage them and -- and take all the money in that you've got on this property and give it to our children.\"","start":3050.311,"stop":3072.35,"duration":22.04},{"text":"That I think is definitely a charge upon that particular property.","start":3072.35,"stop":3077.225,"duration":4.88}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Let's just make it as -- make it as simple, leave mortgages out, say I -- I'd -- I say in my will to my wife, \"You have $100 in your separate property, I'm going to give you $10 if you'll take $10 out of your $100 and give it to our children.\"","start":3077.225,"stop":3094.714,"duration":17.49},{"text":"Now, is the -- is that $10 that I give to her qualifies to the marital deduction?","start":3094.714,"stop":3101.952,"duration":7.24}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir, it does because you are -- you are taxing the $10 and we're concerned with the estate taxes in Mr. Stapf's estate.","start":3101.952,"stop":3111.424,"duration":9.47},{"text":"That's what we're concerned with here.","start":3111.424,"stop":3113.575,"duration":2.15},{"text":"Now, when she gives the $10 to the children --","start":3113.575,"stop":3116.024,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but the idea --","start":3116.024,"stop":3116.456,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that's another --","start":3116.456,"stop":3116.675,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of marital deduction, I thought, was that -- was that the $10 that I left her would increase her estate to $110 and that except for wear and tear and new husbands might stay in her estate.","start":3116.675,"stop":3130.523,"duration":13.85}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's right.","start":3130.523,"stop":3131.597,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And -- but automatically, I prevent that in my will by saying, \"You must divest yourself of $10 (Inaudible).\"","start":3131.597,"stop":3138.999,"duration":7.4}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if you say then that you're going to levy an estate tax with respect to the property that she gives to the children.","start":3138.999,"stop":3150.924,"duration":11.93},{"text":"You're going to levy an estate tax upon that property before she dies.","start":3150.924,"stop":3157.947,"duration":7.02},{"text":"Now, that $10 -- that $10 that comes from her husband, theoretically, maybe in here estate when she dies and will then become subject to --","start":3157.947,"stop":3166.591,"duration":8.64}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But before the martial deduction, what happened?","start":3166.591,"stop":3169.314,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Beg your pardon?","start":3169.314,"stop":3169.995,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Before there was a martial deduction, you didn't -- the husband didn't have deduction at all for the amounts that he gave to his wife, did he?","start":3169.995,"stop":3178.408,"duration":8.41}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":3178.408,"stop":3178.416,"duration":0.01}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"It used to be a provision for property previously taxed before the marital deduction provision in 1948.","start":3178.416,"stop":3185.155,"duration":6.74}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":3185.155,"stop":3185.215,"duration":0.06}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"It used to be a provision for property previously taxed --","start":3185.215,"stop":3186.919,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it was the provision previously taxed.","start":3186.919,"stop":3188.613,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"-- within five years, I think.","start":3188.613,"stop":3189.106,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"W. M. Sutton","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- that's correct.","start":3189.106,"stop":3190.571,"duration":1.46},{"text":"Yes, that would be correct.","start":3190.571,"stop":3194.776,"duration":4.2},{"text":"No -- but in the illustration, the $10 going over to the children, if it is going to be subjected to an estate tax, it's going to be subjected to a tax before the recipient dies.","start":3194.776,"stop":3210.569,"duration":15.79},{"text":"Thank you.","start":3210.569,"stop":3213.751,"duration":3.18}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Barnett.","start":3213.751,"stop":3215.213,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":3215.213,"stop":3217.257,"duration":2.04},{"text":"Well, the Clerk tells me it's not entirely unprecedented.","start":3217.257,"stop":3219.804,"duration":2.55},{"text":"I -- I think the Court would like to know that since this argument began, I'd become a father, and mother and daughter were doing fine.","start":3219.804,"stop":3227.716,"duration":7.91},{"text":"As to the --","start":3227.716,"stop":3228.5,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I didn't understand you.","start":3228.5,"stop":3230.4,"duration":1.9}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"Since the argument began, I'd become a father.","start":3230.4,"stop":3232.868,"duration":2.47},{"text":"I just --","start":3232.868,"stop":3232.997,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh.","start":3232.997,"stop":3235.782,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"As to the other reasons for reversal, I have a -- a few comments.","start":3235.782,"stop":3242.115,"duration":6.33},{"text":"First, the mathematics of the marital -- the mathematics of the marital deduction, a question, assuming that the assumption of the debt is to be treated as a legacy, the question raised by Justice Harlan and Justice White.","start":3242.115,"stop":3260.628,"duration":18.51},{"text":"They're actually very simple.","start":3260.628,"stop":3261.938,"duration":1.31},{"text":"The figures I used yesterday to state for bargain made by the will, started with the net figure of $111,000 as the wife's share of the property.","start":3261.938,"stop":3271.424,"duration":9.49},{"text":"That was after the deduction of the debts and expenses.","start":3271.424,"stop":3275.25,"duration":3.83},{"text":"Now, starting with the gross value of her share of the community property and restating in the bargain in those terms, the bargain that is offered by the will would be this.","start":3275.25,"stop":3286.777,"duration":11.53},{"text":"You have $129,000 worth of community property, gross community property, $129,000.","start":3286.777,"stop":3295.339,"duration":8.56},{"text":"If you will convey all but $85,000 of that, let's say, you convey $44,000 of that to the trust for the children, I would do two things.","start":3295.339,"stop":3306.559,"duration":11.22},{"text":"I will give you $22,000 worth of my property and I will also pay $18,000 worth of your debts and expenses.","start":3306.559,"stop":3314.987,"duration":8.43},{"text":"Therefore, if you will give to the children $44,000, I will give you the benefit of $40,000, so she still comes out $4000 down.I hope that's clear.","start":3314.987,"stop":3330.501,"duration":15.51}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3330.501,"stop":3332.985,"duration":2.48}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":3332.985,"stop":3333.769,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3333.769,"stop":3354.22,"duration":20.45}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":3354.22,"stop":3355.172,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, on the -- on the expenses (Inaudible)","start":3355.172,"stop":3364.279,"duration":9.11}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3364.279,"stop":3365.301,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And there, what (Inaudible)","start":3365.301,"stop":3379.217,"duration":13.92}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":3379.217,"stop":3380.211,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- that's the whole case?","start":3380.211,"stop":3381.557,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the whole case.","start":3381.557,"stop":3383.508,"duration":1.95},{"text":"I think -- I think it is the fact that -- quite that simple.","start":3383.508,"stop":3389.49,"duration":5.98},{"text":"The -- I -- I might point that property previously tax provision, Mr. Justice Stewart, it was still in the statute, actually, it's now become a credit and it doesn't really overlap now deduction problem, I -- I don't believe.","start":3389.49,"stop":3409.526,"duration":20.04},{"text":"The -- and -- but this relates --","start":3409.526,"stop":3413.019,"duration":3.49}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Not confined the spouse is --","start":3413.019,"stop":3413.562,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no, no.","start":3413.562,"stop":3414.68,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the one thing.","start":3414.68,"stop":3415.202,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, his argument -- there's a double tax here because the husband gave her a specific piece of property, blackacre, and blackacre is going to be in her estate and be taxed in her estate.","start":3415.202,"stop":3427.49,"duration":12.29},{"text":"Now, we accept the assumption he makes that what she receives will remain her estate.","start":3427.49,"stop":3432.838,"duration":5.35},{"text":"I think that's a valid assumption to make these purposes.","start":3432.838,"stop":3436.321,"duration":3.48},{"text":"But problem is -- or the blackacre will be in her estate.Securities of the same value are now out of her estate, so it washes out and what the estate tax taxes is economic value, it's not -- not specific pieces of property, blackacre or stock, and it is -- she gets a deduction but his estate gets deduction only for transfer of economic values to -- to the wife and here there was no such transfer.","start":3436.321,"stop":3464.882,"duration":28.56}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3464.882,"stop":3472.031,"duration":7.15}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"The only gift she made to the trust was the excess of $26,000 over 22, namely, $4000 more she added --","start":3472.031,"stop":3480.358,"duration":8.33}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3480.358,"stop":3481.856,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3481.856,"stop":3482.109,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3482.109,"stop":3483.447,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":3483.447,"stop":3484.017,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3484.017,"stop":3503.647,"duration":19.63}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, yes, correct.","start":3503.647,"stop":3505.008,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3505.008,"stop":3505.876,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"She received --","start":3505.876,"stop":3506.379,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3506.379,"stop":3507.031,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, yes.","start":3507.031,"stop":3507.912,"duration":0.88},{"text":"She received consideration for her transfer and any transfer for which you receive consideration is a gift only of the excess over the consideration.","start":3507.912,"stop":3516.608,"duration":8.7}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3516.608,"stop":3518.789,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no.","start":3518.789,"stop":3519.5,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":3519.5,"stop":3526.215,"duration":6.72}]},{"speakerName":"Wayne G. Barnett","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":3526.215,"stop":3526.759,"duration":0.54},{"text":"Of -- of the $26,000 that ends up in the children's trust.","start":3526.759,"stop":3531.045,"duration":4.29},{"text":"We say that $22,000 of that came from the estate indirectly by the exchange but it came from the estate and should be subject to estate tax.","start":3531.045,"stop":3540.25,"duration":9.2},{"text":"The additional $4000 was the wife's contribution and she is liable for gift tax on that amount.","start":3540.25,"stop":3548.181,"duration":7.93},{"text":"Thank you very much.","start":3548.181,"stop":3551.581,"duration":3.4}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Oct  23 - 24, 1963","petitioner":"United States","respondent":"Stapf","docket":"54","citation":"375 US 118 (1963)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/375/118","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Dec 2, 1963"}